pr_body:
Do not run "manual" CI on pull requests as it is being handled by pre-commit.ci now.
Note that pre-commit.ci runs on the commits in PR but "manual" checks just run on the whole repo so they can technically catch something else but it will be outside of PR scope. Doesn't matter much because all checks will run on the push anyway.

Right now on PRs:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12860284/123559152-ed3ffe80-d7a2-11eb-9715-27ba60b22146.png)

After the change, it will be only the last check (that basically runs all of the above). Unfortunately, it can't be split into separate checks.

This is basically a copy of the current OOI workflow with a few changes:
- because Orcasound audio is in stereo obspy creates rather weird spectrograms, it looks like it possibly appends two streams one after another because when I used it first it had 20 sec on the x-axis while recordings are ~10 sec length. I dropped it and switched to scipy for reading wav + matplotlib for plotting.
- new workflow doesn't run on schedule and instead just runs on a manual trigger (can add scheduled runs if desired).
- when run it fetches all files from the latest 'timestamp', so it might be anything between 0-6(?) hours, files are ~10 sec length.
- all files are being converted to .wav using ffmpeg.
- spectrograms are being created for each channel, no bandpass filter or decimate like with obspy. We also passed `dbscale=True, wlen=0.1` when creating OOI spectrograms, here I haven't passed anything.
- all spectrograms are being uploaded like before.
- I've added a step that stitches together all audio files into one (also uploading it).

And I've replaced `print`s with proper logging so we can see which file is being processed in real-time (it was in huge chunks of dozens of lines before, some kind of GitHub output batching I guess).

Around 5.4 hours of data yield 400 MB of spectrograms, quite a lot.

[Example run](https://github.com/Molkree/orca-action-workflow/actions/runs/937541599)
Example spectrogram (it looks like everything above 16-17 kHz can be filtered?):
![live000_spectrogram](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12860284/121976139-dd302400-cd8b-11eb-9c3a-693042c87414.png)

P.S. Hardcoded Bush Point for now.

And I've replaced `print`s with proper logging so we can see which file is being processed in real-time (it was in huge chunks of dozens of lines before, some kind of GitHub output batching I guess).

pr_body:
This is basically a copy of the current OOI workflow with a few changes:
- because Orcasound audio is in stereo obspy creates rather weird spectrograms, it looks like it possibly appends two streams one after another because when I used it first it had 20 sec on the x-axis while recordings are ~10 sec length. I dropped it and switched to scipy for reading wav + matplotlib for plotting.
- new workflow doesn't run on schedule and instead just runs on a manual trigger (can add scheduled runs if desired).
- when run it fetches all files from the latest 'timestamp', so it might be anything between 0-6(?) hours, files are ~10 sec length.
- all files are being converted to .wav using ffmpeg.
- spectrograms are being created for each channel, no bandpass filter or decimate like with obspy. We also passed `dbscale=True, wlen=0.1` when creating OOI spectrograms, here I haven't passed anything.
- all spectrograms are being uploaded like before.
- I've added a step that stitches together all audio files into one (also uploading it).

And I've replaced `print`s with proper logging so we can see which file is being processed in real-time (it was in huge chunks of dozens of lines before, some kind of GitHub output batching I guess).

Around 5.4 hours of data yield 400 MB of spectrograms, quite a lot.

[Example run](https://github.com/Molkree/orca-action-workflow/actions/runs/937541599)
Example spectrogram (it looks like everything above 16-17 kHz can be filtered?):
![live000_spectrogram](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12860284/121976139-dd302400-cd8b-11eb-9c3a-693042c87414.png)

P.S. Hardcoded Bush Point for now.

pr_body: Right now filenames for Orcasound look like `%Y-%m-%dT%H-%M-%S`, so only up to seconds resolution. This is bad because some files are super small (see [here](https://github.com/orcasound/orcanode/issues/32)) hence different files would get the same name -> ffmpeg tries to overwrite the existing file and fails. Quick fix is just to increase the time resolution in filenames (add milliseconds).

pr_body:
- I've reused spectrogram creation from Orcasound, had to modify it a bit to work for mono (OOI) and stereo (Orcasound) signals
- Resulting OOI processing script is really small and self-explanatory but a short overview is:
  For input start/end time, segment length and node:
  1. Get data from OOI using OOIPy (this will interpolate all gaps by default) for each segment
  2. Save it to .wav using OOIPy
  3. Create a spectrogram
Start and end times are as before (previous and today's midnight) so we get data for yesterday.
I've set segment length as 5 minutes because it looks like it is the most common length in OOI data (they also have lots of short recordings).
Node is the same (`PC01A`).
As a result of this loop, we have exactly 288 files (24 hours * 60 minutes / 5 minutes) when previously we were processing each file individually. For example on July 4th there were 375 files total, some of them very short.
Another change: spectrograms. Previously we were applying bandpass filter to only look at the 2-6 kHz, now I just plot everything. Shouldn't matter because it was an example anyway. But we will probably add some parameters to spectrogram creation function to allow this (not in this PR?).

Before:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12860284/124597420-25fb6a00-de6c-11eb-84b1-58bca5312269.png)


After:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12860284/124597435-2bf14b00-de6c-11eb-89f7-d3d10b18dd87.png)

Actually looking at this I should add more info on our spectrograms (wave filename as a title (it will be start time), x axis title and y axis units).

Compare July 4th [old](https://github.com/orcasound/orca-action-workflow/actions/runs/1001108660) and [new](https://github.com/Molkree/orca-action-workflow/actions/runs/1002654455).

pr_title: test(spectrograms): compare np arrays, not files
pr_body:
- fixes #48 

Files have the same size as far as I can see so it probably fails because of the differences in `os.stat` (most likely modification time). Changing it to comparing image arrays fixes the issue for me locally and through CI on my fork. Still, any change to `matplotlib` plotting behavior will probably break this but we'll see.
